##What happened to the people of Wuhan after the city was sealed off

Micro Signal Zhenshigushi1

Function description, every day a moving original true story.

In the early morning of January 23, Wuhan announced that from 10:00, the city's air, rail, city bus, subway, ferry, long-distance passenger transport suspended operation, no special reason, the public do not leave Wuhan. COVID-19 pneumonia is testing the megalopolis of nine provinces.

Over the next 24 hours, the true story project interviewed several residents who chose to stay in Wuhan, as well as doctors, taxi drivers, and food deliverymen, who are in the business of keeping the city afloat, we are trying to understand what is happening to the people left behind in Wuhan, what is the order in the city and what kind of support they need.

The girl who stayed in Wuhan and refused family visits
DICTATION: Chen Dan
Hanyang District, Wuhan. Company clerk
Speaking time: January 23, afternoon
Right now, I'm alone in a rental house in Wuhan. My hometown is four hours'drive from Wuhan.
On January 20th, I had a fever of 102. I do not want to spread the disease to the family, decided to stay alone in Wuhan, I told my parents, Spring Festival is not ready to go home.
In mid January, there were only 41 cases in the news, and the government's propaganda made us feel that we didn't need to panic, so no one around me was wearing a mask. On the evening of the 19th, 77 new cases were suddenly reported overnight, and only then did anyone wear a mask. At this point of illness, I began to want to go to Tongji Hospital, but considering that there is a designated treatment hospital, I was afraid of contact with confirmed patients susceptible to the virus, so I went to a city not so big hospital.
The hospital would send a patient with a bad cough straight to the CT, and I didn't have a bad cough, and the doctor did a blood test, and he determined that I had a viral cold, but he couldn't rule out new pneumonia either. They couldn't confirm the diagnosis, so they gave me an anti-viral shot at the hospital, and then I went back to take my medicine and observe. The doctor told me to go to Tongji Hospital if I have a fever, feel faint, or cough at home, especially if I have no strength or cough.
Now I have a fever, a sore throat, an occasional cough, and strength. But I don't know why, in the heart or very worried, afraid that I am a new type of pneumonia. So now, I keep an eye on my strength.
The doctor told me that only the officially designated fever clinic hospitals such as Tongji, Xiehe and Jinyintan hospital could be confirmed. I was afraid to go there because there were so many people waiting in line. I was afraid that if I didn't get sick, I would catch the virus if I did. So, I had to stay home alone and sterilize every day. I Take Amoxicillin and 999 for colds every day, and some of the drugs against the common flu virus, I can't get them.
I've got 15 masks, 10 n95s, and the rest are surgical masks. Today, I went out and bought some groceries, and then I didn't have to go out. Yesterday I saw the news that alcohol can disinfect, today four nearby pharmacies, alcohol and 84 disinfectant have all been out of stock, I do not know if re-supply now.
You can still get masks if you run around, but they're expensive. My sister buys N95 masks in her hometown. They cost 45 yuan each. They say they are much better now. When I bought it, it was 15 bucks a pop, and my sister was joking, and she said, "you only got 15 bucks for it, so you can sell it to me and make a fortune. ".
I met a patient at the doctor's office, and he was begging the hospital to admit him. I was listening, he judged that he had a new type of pneumonia, originally wanted to go to Tongji Hospital in hospital, but Tongji full. Talking to the doctor, the man kept crying, saying he was scared.
Then a friend in Wuhan sent me some videos. In one video, the hospital is full and everyone is wearing masks. In another video, a woman holds an older man in her arms, shouting for help and crying, "I have a fever, too. " My heart was too long to believe it was a fake video, because I can't imagine a hospital anywhere like this.
Originally, I had a chance to go home before the city was closed, but I volunteered to stay. My family knows I have a cold, want to come to Wuhan City to take care of me, I also stopped. I told them I was safe and that I didn't have a fever. That night, I had nightmares on and off all night, I dreamed I was going to die, and I woke up half an hour later. I had a lot of nightmares in one night. They were very long and very slow.
After the city traffic stopped, I didn't know what I would do if I fell ill, afraid I wouldn't be able to get a taxi.

I knew about the pneumonia, but I didn't care at first
DICTATION: Maya
Wuhan. Company clerk
STORY TIME: January 23, afternoon
I now see the official notice on the Internet, the Health Commission, CCTV news.

It came out in late December, when everyone was terrified, the press release "found no obvious evidence of human-to-human transmission" , and it was announced that eight "disinformation" people had been arrested. I personally feel a little bit bad is, at the beginning of the announcement, refuting rumors, should remind the medical staff and the public to be fully prepared, cause vigilance.
I let my guard down. Someone in the group posted photos of the South China seafood market being blocked and disinfected at the time, and I told her she had better withdraw and wait for the official notice. Don't spread rumors. Officials later dismissed the rumors, although they knew of the presence of pneumonia of unknown origin, but did not care too much.
Later on, the cases started to pile up, and I didn't really care. I think a lot of people are following the official line, and if the official feeling doesn't seem to matter, people let their guard down. Later, I found cases of cases abroad, only really feel not right..
I decided to refund my ticket on the 22nd, and was closed on the 23rd. The News said the outbreak was too contagious and had a long incubation period. My body is a little uncomfortable, just and menstrual period touch together, do not know my discomfort, because of menstrual period, or I have been infected, afraid to go home to family, so a person left in Wuhan. Home alone, scared every day, afraid of what might happen. I'm afraid to go to the hospital. I don't have any symptoms yet. It's more risky.
In the rental house, I pay attention to the room ventilation during the day, go out to wear a warm, wear a mask, come back with medical alcohol wash hands, and then hang clothes to the balcony ventilation place, and then quickly wash your hair to be at ease.
On the day of the siege, I went out to buy some food. Instead of going to the crowded supermarket, I bought cookies, noodles, seasoning, sauce in a small store, and prepared to buy some corn, sweet potato, milk on the e-commerce. I can't cook. I don't buy vegetables or meat. I just need the basic nutrients. Take-out is also afraid to order, can only be so.
When I went out, most of the people on the street were wearing masks, except for a few elderly people. A lot of people are stocking up. Many people buy face masks in drugstores, many of which are out of stock, and many of which are sold out of disinfectant. Instead of buying disinfectant, I brought home a dozen face masks and a thermometer. Nothing I bought went up in price. The thermometer cost $8. The only face masks I bought from the pharmacy were the medical care masks for prudent care, which cost $1.50 each. To make sure everyone could buy them, I only bought 15 for each.
Except for me, most of my colleagues went home on the 21st and 22nd. They all need to be better prepared. I reminded my colleagues back home to be in protective isolation, wearing a mask to eat, because the incubation period really does not see, no one knows whether they are carriers. But they said to me, the infection is estimated to be something physically wrong with the elderly, children and adolescents rarely get the disease. I think it's too optimistic.

People waiting for the supermarket to open in the wee hours
DICTATION: Zeng Erchun
Wuchang District, Wuhan, the publishing industry
The evening of January 23
At 3:05 a.m. on January 23,2020, I was woken up by a call from a friend. She said bluntly, just saw Wuhan Notice 23 at 10:00 AM will be closed to the city's news, asked me whether I have seen, on the phone to read the notice of the prevention and Control Command, also advised me to stock up on supplies. After hanging up the phone and confirming the information, I contacted other friends in Wuhan and decided to go out early in the morning to shop.
I don't live near a 24-hour convenience store. Even if there is, the convenience store can not meet my personal needs to eat and use. So I decided to head out early and shop at the big box store. In recent days, Wuhan's Road and people are less, morning no car, all the way smooth. When I got to the supermarket, the supermarket was not open yet, but several citizens had already arrived. They all stood in the doorway and waited.
The shopping took about an hour. I don't know if it's because of the early departure, but the supermarket is full. The line at the checkout wasn't as long as it used to be when I came home from work. Back home, I saw a cabbage in the Internet to sell dozens of pictures, deliberately went to see I bought a cabbage price tag, no difference with normal, as long as three more. But I haven't been out since I got home a little after 9:00 in the morning, and I don't know if the prices have changed.
True story | 9:30 am, Jan 23, at a supermarket in Wuhan
My friend in the fresh platform online shopping, I talked to the phone after the early hours of the order, the same afternoon to the. Normally, the platform would be here an hour or two after work.
Wuhan now public transport is suspended, taxi is also relatively rare (also limited number) , and soon the online car also stopped. There were fewer takeout guys on the road than usual. I do not plan to go out during the city, just stay at home to catch up on drama, play games, to avoid trouble. After all, I was in the "hard-hit areas" of the epidemic. I was busy cleaning and sterilizing the house before I started to have fun. At the end of the day, the game almost broke as a joke.
I was watching the news the other day, and I saw a map of the current outbreak. The gradually reddened areas of infection reminded me of the mobile phone game "Plague.Inc. ". I haven't played in three years. It's still in my phone. In Wuhan, and in the atmosphere of the closed city, click on this game is almost visual sense Max. These two days, inexplicably, several particularly difficult levels I have played a good score, probably because I am in the epidemic area of the cause of it (laughter) , it is also a bittersweet.

Citizens stopped cars at the side of the road and said they would go anywhere they could get out of Wuhan
DICTATION: Xu Shan
Wuhan Hongshan District, taxi driver
Speaking time: January 23, afternoon
Wuhan used to be a city that never sleeps.
On the night of January 21st, I was driving down the road, and I didn't realize the severity of the pneumonia until after 8:00. Throughout the day, news has been coming in and the number of confirmed cases has been increasing.
I left on January 22 wearing a mask and carrying a bottle of 84 disinfectant. Every passenger I take, I have to sterilize, door handles, seat cushions and other passengers can touch the place, I have sprayed disinfection water, and then wipe again.
Later that afternoon, when I sent a friend to another city, there were fewer cars in Wuhan. I saw among the drivers that the taxi drivers in the city were off duty at about 8 o'clock. On the way back to the city after dropping off my friend, I was stopped. The staff took my temperature with an electronic thermometer. I was allowed to pass only when there was no problem.
By 6:54 a.m. on January 23, I had received a text message from the passenger management office informing us that traffic control would be imposed after 10 a.m. and that public transportation would be suspended throughout the city, so our taxis would become an important mode of transportation for the city. The message calls on us to abide by professional and social ethics, do not refuse to carry, detour, take the opportunity to blackmail money. After that, I walked my bus driver back to Hankou, only to find that taxis and a handful of online hailing services were available. When I dropped him off, I passed the south China Seafood Market, which had been boarded up, and now it's a no man's land.
After dropping off a colleague, I went back to Wuchang around 10:30. As I passed the Wuchang Railway Station, I saw silence and a faint glimpse of medical staff in the station, presumably for emergencies. There were more pedestrians on the side of the road than the day before, and many people with suitcases, wearing masks, were waiting for the bus.
Photo of a Wuhan resident waiting for a bus
These people want to get out of the city, I heard them say, as long as they can get out of Wuhan, anywhere, the price is high. I got out of the car, made a little video of it, posted it to the family group, and then I left. In fact, out of the people, will be stopped on the highway temperature, sprayed on clothing disinfection water, temperature normal people can go out.
Most of the people who are still driving today (the 23rd) feel that business is bad this year and want to take a risk and make some money. On the other hand, with no public transportation, people want to contribute.
Drivers are happy to pick up anyone who isn't on the way to the hospital. Seeing people with hospital bags in their hands, people get scared, even with the best of precautions. People going to the hospital also know that drivers are afraid, in order to get into the car, some of them will block in front of the car, want to get on the ground. Such passengers, often have done in place of their own protection, wearing masks, we drove them to the hospital, only can do is to wear masks, disinfection, no cash, less communication.
I remember the day of January 21, I took a passenger to Wuhan Central Hospital, when everything was normal. There were taxis waiting outside the hospital, as if there were no more.
These two days, I come home after the first thing is to change clothes, take a bath, home has a child, even if I have an accident, also can not infect a child. I'm not going out from today. It's Chinese New Year. This year, Wuhan New Year, relatives do not move, not happy new year is the characteristics of this Spring Festival.

Lack of protective clothing among frontline staff
DICTATION: Huang Zhuo
Wuhan Tongji Hospital, Doctor
The evening of January 23
What I learned about the shortage of kits is that tens of thousands of kits have been produced by reagent companies, including Geno and Pfizer. The Kit was sent down, but it was not used, and it was not known how many links went wrong. My Hospital Examination Department is also very anxious, wants to do actually can not do for the patient.
We're on the last shift today, but we're on call after that, so we'll be here if you need us. Non-special period our section is mainly responsible for surgical patient diagnosis, guidance, prognosis, so, this pneumonia we were not the first-line section, in fact, not helpful. It's just that it's spread so widely that all the departments in the basic hospital are affected -- as if, for one, every department has a front desk for patients, and there's a risk of infection, and secondly, many of the families in our department are on the clinical front lines, many front-line personnel are quarantined for suspected infection, and they are at risk of infection.
I have a colleague, her husband in the Concord Hospital Line, so for the sake of the safety of other departments, she was placed in isolation. Good thing we know she's okay. She doesn't have pneumonia.
We will worry, but we still have to do the clinical work, this time as a medical staff, a strong sense of mission.
There have been cases of COVID-19 pneumonia in our hospital for a long time (officially December 27) . At that time, because could not find out the reason, we highly suspected SARS, began to respond to protective measures. Later, more and more people had the same symptoms, and by the time the panel came down in late December, we were already worried that it was getting worse. We tried to raise the alarm a couple of times in the friend zone, but it struck me as sad that it wasn't the people in the zone who were really defenseless and thought we were making a fuss and doing what we were supposed to do. Coupled with the early health commission said that no human-to-human transmission, continued low infectious power of the official statement, people even more do not think.
Early January is already very serious, early on the exact number of patients admitted is not clear. There's four floors in the suction department, about 300 beds. I guess a week ago there was a shortage of beds and people. After the new medical building of the hospital was completed, the old medical building was vacated and started to be renovated. Because of the lack of beds, this time a floor was allocated directly to the Department of Infectious Diseases. About 100 beds could be added, but it was not enough. As far as I know, some hospitals have even requisitioned dermatology and endocrinology wards as fever wards, while others, which originally had only two suction wards, have been expanded to six wards in two weeks.
The room smelled of disinfectant, because we fumigated it with 1:100 of 84 disinfectant every day.
Normally, second-line staff who do not have direct contact with patients need only wear masks, but fever clinics, ambulances on duty, Ward staff must wear protective clothing. The current situation is that there is a limited number of protective clothing, but also a one-time, conditions do not allow everyone to wear. As far as I know, so far, our hospital and other hospitals are in short supply of protective clothing, some of the front-line medical staff can not wear protective clothing.
We have to wear masks in the department, but from about January 21, in order to ensure first-line material needs, masks priority supply fever clinics and wards. In other departments and hospitals, a daily limit of 2 general surgical masks per person is set. We bought the N95 ourselves, and now we can't get it.
These days, I see many hospitals are asking for social support, city children, a hospital, two hospitals, provincial Chinese medicine, central South, concord and so on. Most let a person be angry is, still have cheater to use his mobile phone number to pass off hospital to Cheat Fund on the net now. At present, our hospital has also begun to ask for social assistance, hope to be able to get social material assistance.

Face masks sold out on first day of closure
Dictation: Wu Yi
Delivery man, Hongshan District, Wuhan City
Speaking time: January 24 am
On January 23rd, just after 2 am, when I saw the news of the city closure on Weibo, my first reaction was: finished, forgot to buy something to eat and drink at home. Later I felt that leaders at all levels of government should take this into account, and I was not too worried.

That day, I sent a dozen orders, the vast majority of the orders are related to protective supplies, masks, hand sanitizer, and some are grain and oil, snacks, instant noodles. A little after 11:00, when I went to pick up some vegetables at a market on the way to Xudong, Hongshan District, I found that many vegetable vendors in the market had closed up, the vegetables had been sold out, and there were still many stalls selling meat left.
When I went to pick it up after 3:30 p.m. , more and more businesses told us they were out of masks. One person ordered a mask, I picked up the goods, found to take is non-woven masks and cotton masks, I told the shopkeeper, wearing this mask is useless, shopkeeper said she did not know, thanked me, said to find a way to buy some good masks to sell.
Screenshot of the day's orders
Yesterday, orders were still being delivered to the hospital. At first, no one would take the order, but the list would continue to hang on the APP, and the platform or merchant would add a reward, and if the delivery fee was high enough, someone would want to give it away. However, riders also communicate with each other and try not to take them to the outpatient infusion unit, which is known to be in a state of chaos.
At 2 or 3 o'clock in the afternoon, on my way to deliver food, I found that two nearby shopping malls were closed. I turned on the take-out software and closed my usual pot-boiled Rice. Then I began to worry. I realized that there was no dinner for me at night, so I went to buy some instant noodles, but there's no extra food in store. I asked around the neighborhood for convenience stores, fruit stands, and small supermarket chains, and they said they would keep the doors open. When I went out this morning, I found that all the doors were open, and I didn't feel like I had to worry about food.
My delivery place in Wuhan is a relatively prosperous area, usually the road is very blocked. Yesterday, there was no bus on the road, private cars are refueling, the rest of the road is very smooth, only the gas station intersection traffic jam. There are few pedestrians on the streets, 90 percent of young people wear masks, and some older people do not wear masks.
Some customers are more cautious, when delivering to him, they will stay away, or the door open a small crack, take things in.
In the early hours of the 22nd, a pneumonia patient was found in the neighborhood next door, and police cars and paramedics arrived. When I heard about it, I started to be a little bit scared, because there are four hospitals in my delivery area, and I've been delivering to them since January, and I've been delivering to them lately.
Now that I think about it, when I started taking orders to the hospital in mid-january, I felt that there were more and more people waiting at the outpatient clinic for IV treatment, mostly with masks on. The hospital itself didn't seem to have any protection, and a lot of the doctors weren't wearing masks. At the time, I thought it was flu season, and fevers were common.
I didn't put on a mask until after January 21, when the news reports of the outbreak began to get worse. It didn't seem that serious before, and no one told us to take it seriously.
From January 22, the delivery platform began to repeatedly remind us to wear masks, wash our hands, pay attention to personal hygiene, to disinfect the dinner box. Along with it, more and more people buy masks, and many of the orders are masks, protective equipment, we began to pay attention to them.
On the same day, when I delivered food, I saw some neighborhoods where the cleaning staff were sterilizing the elevators, some neighborhoods would not let the delivery staff in, some neighborhoods would set up infrared temperature measuring devices at the door, and people coming in and out of the neighborhoods would raise their hands for a temperature test.
My hometown is northwest Hubei, this year's Spring Festival, because something to deal with, I have no plans to go home. After seeing the news of the closing of the city, the first worry was whether the younger brother working in Wuhan could go home. Then I thought about the future of the city. Can we still do our jobs? I've never seen anything like it.
Today is the New Year's Eve, it is raining in Wuhan, I did not deliver food. When I went downstairs to buy canned gruel, I was rejected because I didn't wear a mask. The convenience store owner forced me to wear a cotton mask, which wasn't much use, but it was warm.
Tomorrow I'll put on a mask, gloves, wet paper towels and alcohol to sterilize myself, my electric car and my lunch box, and get back to work.

People waiting for the supermarket to open in the wee hours

They all stood in the doorway and waited.

The shopping took about an hour. I don't know if it's because of the early departure, but the supermarket is full. The line at the checkout wasn't as long as it used to be when I came home from work. Back home, I saw a cabbage in the Internet to sell dozens of pictures, deliberately went to see I bought a cabbage price tag, no difference with normal, as long as three more. But I haven't been out since I got home a little after 9:00 in the morning, and I don't know if the prices have changed.

True story | 9:30 am, Jan 23, at a supermarket in Wuhan

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
My friend in the fresh platform online shopping, I talked to the phone after the early hours of the order, the same afternoon to the. Normally, the platform would be here an hour or two after work.

Wuhan now public transport is suspended, taxi is also relatively rare (also limited number) , and soon the online car also stopped. There were fewer takeout guys on the road than usual. I do not plan to go out during the city, just stay at home to catch up on drama, play games, to avoid trouble. After all, I was in the "hard-hit areas" of the epidemic. I was busy cleaning and sterilizing the house before I started to have fun. At the end of the day, the game almost broke as a joke.

I was watching the news the other day, and I saw a map of the current outbreak. The gradually reddened areas of infection reminded me of the mobile phone game "Plague.Inc. ". I haven't played in three years. It's still in my phone. In Wuhan, and in the atmosphere of the closed city, click on this game is almost visual sense Max. These two days, inexplicably, several particularly difficult levels I have played a good score, probably because I am in the epidemic area of the cause of it (laughter) , it is also a bittersweet.

Citizens stopped cars at the side of the road and said they would go anywhere they could get out of Wuhan

DICTATION: Xu Shan

Wuhan Hongshan District, taxi driver

Wuhan used to be a city that never sleeps.

On the night of January 21st, I was driving down the road, and I didn't realize the severity of the pneumonia until after 8:00. Throughout the day, news has been coming in and the number of confirmed cases has been increasing.

I left on January 22 wearing a mask and carrying a bottle of 84 disinfectant. Every passenger I take, I have to sterilize, door handles, seat cushions and other passengers can touch the place, I have sprayed disinfection water, and then wipe again.

Later that afternoon, when I sent a friend to another city, there were fewer cars in Wuhan. I saw among the drivers that the taxi drivers in the city were off duty at about 8 o'clock. On the way back to the city after dropping off my friend, I was stopped. The staff took my temperature with an electronic thermometer. I was allowed to pass only when there was no problem.

By 6:54 a.m. on January 23, I had received a text message from the passenger management office informing us that traffic control would be imposed after 10 a.m. and that public transportation would be suspended throughout the city, so our taxis would become an important mode of transportation for the city. The message calls on us to abide by professional and social ethics, do not refuse to carry, detour, take the opportunity to blackmail money. After that, I walked my bus driver back to Hankou, only to find that taxis and a handful of online hailing services were available. When I dropped him off, I passed the south China Seafood Market, which had been boarded up, and now it's a no man's land.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
After dropping off a colleague, I went back to Wuchang around 10:30. As I passed the Wuchang Railway Station, I saw silence and a faint glimpse of medical staff in the station, presumably for emergencies. There were more pedestrians on the side of the road than the day before, and many people with suitcases, wearing masks, were waiting for the bus.

Photo of a Wuhan resident waiting for a bus

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
These people want to get out of the city, I heard them say, as long as they can get out of Wuhan, anywhere, the price is high. I got out of the car, made a little video of it, posted it to the family group, and then I left. In fact, out of the people, will be stopped on the highway temperature, sprayed on clothing disinfection water, temperature normal people can go out.

Most of the people who are still driving today (the 23rd) feel that business is bad this year and want to take a risk and make some money. On the other hand, with no public transportation, people want to contribute.

Drivers are happy to pick up anyone who isn't on the way to the hospital. Seeing people with hospital bags in their hands, people get scared, even with the best of precautions. People going to the hospital also know that drivers are afraid, in order to get into the car, some of them will block in front of the car, want to get on the ground. Such passengers, often have done in place of their own protection, wearing masks, we drove them to the hospital, only can do is to wear masks, disinfection, no cash, less communication.

I remember the day of January 21, I took a passenger to Wuhan Central Hospital, when everything was normal. There were taxis waiting outside the hospital, as if there were no more.

These two days, I come home after the first thing is to change clothes, take a bath, home has a child, even if I have an accident, also can not infect a child. I'm not going out from today. It's Chinese New Year. This year, Wuhan New Year, relatives do not move, not happy new year is the characteristics of this Spring Festival.

Lack of protective clothing among frontline staff

DICTATION: Huang Zhuo

Wuhan Tongji Hospital, Doctor

What I learned about the shortage of kits is that tens of thousands of kits have been produced by reagent companies, including Geno and Pfizer. The Kit was sent down, but it was not used, and it was not known how many links went wrong. My Hospital Examination Department is also very anxious, wants to do actually can not do for the patient.

We're on the last shift today, but we're on call after that, so we'll be here if you need us. Non-special period our section is mainly responsible for surgical patient diagnosis, guidance, prognosis, so, this pneumonia we were not the first-line section, in fact, not helpful. It's just that it's spread so widely that all the departments in the basic hospital are affected -- as if, for one, every department has a front desk for patients, and there's a risk of infection, and secondly, many of the families in our department are on the clinical front lines, many front-line personnel are quarantined for suspected infection, and they are at risk of infection.

I have a colleague, her husband in the Concord Hospital Line, so for the sake of the safety of other departments, she was placed in isolation. Good thing we know she's okay. She doesn't have pneumonia.

We will worry, but we still have to do the clinical work, this time as a medical staff, a strong sense of mission.

There have been cases of COVID-19 pneumonia in our hospital for a long time (officially December 27) . At that time, because could not find out the reason, we highly suspected SARS, began to respond to protective measures. Later, more and more people had the same symptoms, and by the time the panel came down in late December, we were already worried that it was getting worse. We tried to raise the alarm a couple of times in the friend zone, but it struck me as sad that it wasn't the people in the zone who were really defenseless and thought we were making a fuss and doing what we were supposed to do. Coupled with the early health commission said that no human-to-human transmission, continued low infectious power of the official statement, people even more do not think.

Early January is already very serious, early on the exact number of patients admitted is not clear. There's four floors in the suction department, about 300 beds. I guess a week ago there was a shortage of beds and people. After the new medical building of the hospital was completed, the old medical building was vacated and started to be renovated. Because of the lack of beds, this time a floor was allocated directly to the Department of Infectious Diseases. About 100 beds could be added, but it was not enough. As far as I know, some hospitals have even requisitioned dermatology and endocrinology wards as fever wards, while others, which originally had only two suction wards, have been expanded to six wards in two weeks.

The room smelled of disinfectant, because we fumigated it with 1:100 of 84 disinfectant every day.

Normally, second-line staff who do not have direct contact with patients need only wear masks, but fever clinics, ambulances on duty, Ward staff must wear protective clothing. The current situation is that there is a limited number of protective clothing, but also a one-time, conditions do not allow everyone to wear. As far as I know, so far, our hospital and other hospitals are in short supply of protective clothing, some of the front-line medical staff can not wear protective clothing.

We have to wear masks in the department, but from about January 21, in order to ensure first-line material needs, masks priority supply fever clinics and wards. In other departments and hospitals, a daily limit of 2 general surgical masks per person is set. We bought the N95 ourselves, and now we can't get it.

These days, I see many hospitals are asking for social support, city children, a hospital, two hospitals, provincial Chinese medicine, central South, concord and so on. Most let a person be angry is, still have cheater to use his mobile phone number to pass off hospital to Cheat Fund on the net now. At present, our hospital has also begun to ask for social assistance, hope to be able to get social material assistance.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Face masks sold out on first day of closure

Dictation: Wu Yi

Delivery man, Hongshan District, Wuhan City

Speaking time: January 24 am

On January 23rd, just after 2 am, when I saw the news of the city closure on Weibo, my first reaction was: finished, forgot to buy something to eat and drink at home. Later I felt that leaders at all levels of government should take this into account, and I was not too worried.

That day, I sent a dozen orders, the vast majority of the orders are related to protective supplies, masks, hand sanitizer, and some are grain and oil, snacks, instant noodles. A little after 11:00, when I went to pick up some vegetables at a market on the way to Xudong, Hongshan District, I found that many vegetable vendors in the market had closed up, the vegetables had been sold out, and there were still many stalls selling meat left.

When I went to pick it up after 3:30 p.m. , more and more businesses told us they were out of masks. One person ordered a mask, I picked up the goods, found to take is non-woven masks and cotton masks, I told the shopkeeper, wearing this mask is useless, shopkeeper said she did not know, thanked me, said to find a way to buy some good masks to sell.

Screenshot of the day's orders

Yesterday, orders were still being delivered to the hospital. At first, no one would take the order, but the list would continue to hang on the APP, and the platform or merchant would add a reward, and if the delivery fee was high enough, someone would want to give it away. However, riders also communicate with each other and try not to take them to the outpatient infusion unit, which is known to be in a state of chaos.

At 2 or 3 o'clock in the afternoon, on my way to deliver food, I found that two nearby shopping malls were closed. I turned on the take-out software and closed my usual pot-boiled Rice. Then I began to worry. I realized that there was no dinner for me at night, so I went to buy some instant noodles, but there's no extra food in store. I asked around the neighborhood for convenience stores, fruit stands, and small supermarket chains, and they said they would keep the doors open. When I went out this morning, I found that all the doors were open, and I didn't feel like I had to worry about food.

My delivery place in Wuhan is a relatively prosperous area, usually the road is very blocked. Yesterday, there was no bus on the road, private cars are refueling, the rest of the road is very smooth, only the gas station intersection traffic jam. There are few pedestrians on the streets, 90 percent of young people wear masks, and some older people do not wear masks.

Some customers are more cautious, when delivering to him, they will stay away, or the door open a small crack, take things in.

In the early hours of the 22nd, a pneumonia patient was found in the neighborhood next door, and police cars and paramedics arrived. When I heard about it, I started to be a little bit scared, because there are four hospitals in my delivery area, and I've been delivering to them since January, and I've been delivering to them lately.

Now that I think about it, when I started taking orders to the hospital in mid-january, I felt that there were more and more people waiting at the outpatient clinic for IV treatment, mostly with masks on. The hospital itself didn't seem to have any protection, and a lot of the doctors weren't wearing masks. At the time, I thought it was flu season, and fevers were common.

I didn't put on a mask until after January 21, when the news reports of the outbreak began to get worse. It didn't seem that serious before, and no one told us to take it seriously.

From January 22, the delivery platform began to repeatedly remind us to wear masks, wash our hands, pay attention to personal hygiene, to disinfect the dinner box. Along with it, more and more people buy masks, and many of the orders are masks, protective equipment, we began to pay attention to them.

On the same day, when I delivered food, I saw some neighborhoods where the cleaning staff were sterilizing the elevators, some neighborhoods would not let the delivery staff in, some neighborhoods would set up infrared temperature measuring devices at the door, and people coming in and out of the neighborhoods would raise their hands for a temperature test.

My hometown is northwest Hubei, this year's Spring Festival, because something to deal with, I have no plans to go home. After seeing the news of the closing of the city, the first worry was whether the younger brother working in Wuhan could go home. Then I thought about the future of the city. Can we still do our jobs? I've never seen anything like it.

Today is the New Year's Eve, it is raining in Wuhan, I did not deliver food. When I went downstairs to buy canned gruel, I was rejected because I didn't wear a mask. The convenience store owner forced me to wear a cotton mask, which wasn't much use, but it was warm.

Tomorrow I'll put on a mask, gloves, wet paper towels and alcohol to sterilize myself, my electric car and my lunch box, and get back to work.

* To protect the privacy of the interviewees, some of the articles were written under pseudonyms.
